  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(14) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Jair took . . . unto this day.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The last words of this chapter seem to point to a later hand, as of Joshua, describing the completion of the conquest. The expression “unto this day” is characteristically common in Joshua, or in the editorial notes inserted throughout that book. (See ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Introduction ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "to Joshua, “On the Style of the Book.”)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Geshuri and Maachathi—i.e., the Geshurite and the Maachathite, the inhabitants of Geshur and Maachah. “The Maachathites, near the Jordan springs (comp. Abel-Beth-maachah, 2Samuel 20:14-15), and the Geshurites, rather farther east” (Conder, Bible Handbook, p. 254). Talmai, king of Geshur, was the grandfather of Absalom (2Samuel 3:3), who took refuge with him after he killed Ammon (2Samuel 13:37). “Argob, Trachonitis, or El-Lejja, has been an asylum for all malefactors and refugees ever since” (Giant Cities of Bashan, p. 92).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Geshuri and Maachathi",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "i.e., ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "the Geshurite and the Maachathite, the inhabitants of Geshur and Maachah. “The Maachathites, near the Jordan springs (comp. Abel-Beth-maachah, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 20:14-15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), and the Geshurites, rather farther east” (Conder, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Bible Handbook, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "p. 254). Talmai, king of Geshur, was the grandfather of Absalom (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 3:3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "), who took refuge with him after he killed Ammon (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Samuel 13:37",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). “Argob, Trachonitis, or El-Lejja, has been an asylum for all malefactors and refugees ever since” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Giant Cities of Bashan, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "p. 92).",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
